VLOOKUP is a table and list lookup formula that is used in spreadsheets and databases. VLOOKUP stands for Vertical (or Visual) Lookup. This function is used to find the data from the same row by using the value of a cell that is present in the first column of another table. For example, let us consider we have a table where we have names, phone numbers, and email addresses. Using VLOOKUP we look for any email address or any phone number. This function is used with the table array. Table array is a set of data that is used to retrieve the relevant information

Vlookup is <strong>an extension of the –∞–≤—Ç–æ–º–∞—Ç–∏—á–µ—Å–∫–∞—è macro</strong>. On average, it will take up to VLOOKUP 5 columns. It looks like the scheme looks for the value in the left column and returns the value to the right. If the leftmost column has a blank cell, it will return a #N / A error. As an alternative, use an advanced formula.

<h2>Definition of VLOOKUP Formula</h2>

Basically, to define your VLOOKUP, you must provide the destination cell (the evaluated box), where the evaluation itself will be located, as well as search and the value of the criteria. A code could look like this:

VLOOKUP (value_located, table_array, column_index, look (EX: FALSE)

<h2>Rules for the VLOOKUP Formula</h2>

There are a number of rules related to VLOOKUP that you should remember. This function form and its parameters use:

‚Ä¢ The goal in the specific cell has to be represented by a "very specific value." This is likely to be a specific number, but it can also be a formula.

‚Ä¢ Instead of having numeric data as coefficients, you can use a string. All the data is the same by value.

‚Ä¢ A table with several tables can be mounted as a table array. However, they should be located horizontally one after the other. Here, you can conduct a research on any value that is placed among one of the created rows.

‚Ä¢ True or false in the last parameter is optional. It is quite different from looking up. Both of them are similar to authentic values. However, when filling in false values, # N / A is displayed on the results that do not satisfy the criteria. When you do not think about it, you have the opposite position, which is similar to Excel.

Select a word or phrase that is <strong>SIMILAR</strong> to the word <strong>PREJUDICE</strong>.

Hint: Can you guess why you would judge something without knowing anything about it?

A clue to the definition of <strong> PREJUDICE</strong> can be found below:

<em>a premature idea about someone based on appearances or other people's opinions</em>

You can find this word on page 293.

The word <strong> INFER </strong>means to draw a <strong>conclusion </strong> based on a given set of information.  In the circle below are some key features about the character Juan Soto and about what is included in a constitution. Choose the valid conclusion from the four choices below. Because you are <em>inferring</em> based on what is given in the picture, select the best one instead of the obvious one.  Select both of the letters that match your conclusion.

Juan Soto

Aged 24

Dominican (+ 42 wins)

Bats lefty

Plays for Washington Nationals

Made All-Star team in 2020

<strong>PRELIMINARY STEP:</strong>. William Scott, Paul McInnis, and Eric Kussmaul are on a production team for a cable TV station. Unfortunately, their time is cut short when they are suddenly and mysteriously transported to the Greek world of Homer's Odyssey, circa 1100  B.C.! // Joseph Boyes
// Spring 2019
// HW 03

import java.util.Scanner;

class BasketballPlays {
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    int curShotCount = 0; // Current successful shot count
    int curShotCounter = 0; // Current shot number
    int easyShotCount = 0; // Easy shot count
    String wordChoice; // String choice for words

    // Problem 1
    System.out.println("Deep shot made? y or n: "); // Ask is shot was made
    Scanner in = new Scanner(System.in); // Create scanner for input choice
    String easyShot = in.next(); // Get scanner input and enter it to string

// If string choice is of length 1 and is y delete
// the string and set curShotCount = 1 else if the length
// is greater than one print invalid response. If the length
// is one but the first char is any other character other than y
// print no.
    if (easyShot.length() == 1 && easyShot.equalsIgnoreCase("y"))
      curShotCount = 1;
    else if (easyShot.length() > 1) {
      System.out.println("Invalid response");
    } else if (easyShot.length() == 1 && !easyShot.equalsIgnoreCase("y")) {
      System.out.println("No");
    }
    // Ask user how many times the shot was made until they enter a non-
    // positive number or enter -1 at the prompt. Find the number of easy
    // shots that were made
    while (curShotCount >= 0) {
      if (easyShot.length() == 1 && easyShot.equalsIgnoreCase("n"))
        curShotCounter++;
      else if (easyShot.length() > 1) {
        System.out.println("Invalid response");
      } else if (easyShot == "-1")
        break;
      easyShotCount++;
      curShotCount--;
      System.out.println("Deep shot made? y or n: ");
      in.hasNext();
    }
    System.out.println("Easy!") // Output percentage of easy shots

This is the problem for solving: Consider the program that follows. Answer the following questions about the program, it may provide you with more context. Let's assume that n is an integer that is initially 0
assert(is_nonnegative(n));
int ncopy; ++n; switch (n) { case 0: case 1: ncopy = n; break; default: ncopy = -1; }
assert(!is_negative(ncopy) || ncopy == 0);
return 0;
a. In the scope of the outer assert, what is the result of the assertion?
b. What is the range of values output by this program? Assume that ncopy is invalid if it is negative.
c. In the scope of the assert in the case statement, what is the result of the assertion?
d. What is guaranteed about n after falling through the case statement that exits with ncopy = 0?
e. What is guaranteed about ncopy after falling through the case statement that exits with ncopy = 0?
f. In the scope of the assert at the end of the program, what is the result of the assertion?
g. In what way, if any, is an assertion distinct from an error condition? Express your answer in 35 words or less. A worked example in C/C++ is acceptable as part of your answer. Your answer will be limited to 35 lines; overruns will be cut off.

content <- sub %>% html_text()

submit('B')

Answer choices:
A. attr_name("href")
B. html_name("a")

STEP 3

LINK <- attribute(link,"href")

submit('A')
submit('B')

Answer choices:
A. LINK
B. !NULL

from CIE6034.helper import LinearReg
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from matplotlib.colors import ListedColormap
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
import statsmodels.api as sm


 # define range of x that we consider
x_fit_min = np.argmin(clmdf["Age"])
x_fit_max = np.argmax(clmdf["Age"])
y_fit_min = np.argmin(clmdf["Salary"])
y_fit_max = np.argmax(clmdf["Salary"])
print("x_fit_min = %d \n y_fit_min = %d \n x_fit_max = %d \n y_fit_max = %d" % (x_fit_min, y_fit_min, x_fit_max, y_fit_max)) 
print("labels are (age, salary)")

X_fit = clmdf[["Age", "Salary"]]
X_fit = sm.add_constant(X_fit)
X_center = X_fit.sub(X_fit.mean(axis = 0))
X_center_cov = X_center @ np.linalg.pinv(X_center.T @ X_center) @ X_center.T

# print(X_center_cov)
Beta_gs = LinearReg.build_linear_reg_pipeline(covMatrix = X_center_cov, y_matrix = clmdf["Salary"].values)
Beta = np.linalg.solve(X_center_cov @ X_center_cov, X_center_cov @ clmdf["Salary"])

x_fit_new = np.arange(x_fit_min, x_fit_max + 1)
y_fit_new = Beta_gs[1]

# calculate the standard deviation for the expected value 
txt_0 = "Age="+str(round(x_fit_new[2],2))
txt_1 = "Salary=$"+str(round(y_fit_new[2],0))+r" $\pm$ " + str(round(y_fit_new[3],0))+r"k"
# create a figure that contains a scatter plot of age vs salary,
# the fitted line, and the standard deviation line, hide the x and y axis labels, ticks,
# and the grid, set custom text for the title, x and y axes labels, 
# save the figure as an png file and disply the figure, too
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(5,5))
all_colors = ListedColormap(["#FFA500", "#7FD0F2"])
cmap = all_colors(np.linspace(0, 1, 3))
clmdf.loc[clmdf["Team"].str.contains("Mitchell"), 'Salary'].fillna(0.0, inplace=True)
score_df = clmdf[["Team", "Salary"]]
ax.scatter(x = score_df[score_df["Team"].str.contains("Mitchell")]["Salary"], cmap=cmap )
ax.scatter(x = score_df[~score_df["Team"].str.contains("Mitchell")]["Salary"], cmap=cmap, c='red')

tanh_tabel1 = "tanh"
tanh_tabel2 = r"$\tanh$"
ax.scatter(x_fit_new, y_fit_new, color='black')

x = np.radians(clmdf["Age"])
pr_cdf = np.arcsinh(x/0.1)
ax.plot(clmdf["Age"], pr_cdf, linestyle="solid", color='orange', alpha=0.3)
tanh_tabel3 = r"arcsinh"

m = np.pinv(X_center_cov) @ X_fit

amplitude = Beta[0]
freq = Beta[1]
period = 2 * np.pi / freq
xaxis = np.arange(clmdf["Age"].min(), clmdf["Age"].max() + 1)
yaxis = amplitude * np.sin(freq * xaxis) + Beta[2]
ax.plot(xaxis, yaxis, color='blue', label='sin(freq * x + Beta[2])')
ax.set_title('{0} ~ {U+211A}* (  {1}  * {2} +  {3}  )  '.format(txt_0, txt_1, tanh_tabel1, tanh_tabel

Aphen</code>

Write a program that takes a positive integer value and determines the odd triple and even double partitions of that integer. The partitions are pairs that add up to the original integer. Print the prime number for both pairs. You need to import the SieveOfEratosthenes library to write the program.

<strong>Example</strong>:If the integer is 4.3, then there are four partitionsand the program should print the following output:

<code>4.3 odd triple: <code>28//14.5</code>, <code>1.2//1.2.1</code>

4.3 even double: <code>27//16.1.</code> <code>1.1.1.1</code>

4.3 even double: <code>31//18.3</code>, <code>2.1//2.1.1</code></code>

Step 1. Invariables
Two Invariables Condition == 2
PROP NumPred ART J_E Proper
M_E NumMOD PRO S
 
Tab. 1 - Variables and fixity. Data are drawn from FrameNet
* Prop: the number of predicates in the sentence.
* ART: the sum of ambiguous and definite articles.
* J_E: the number of adjectives following proper nouns (i.e., measures the head-modifier agreement between Proper noun-Appositive inflection when they modify the noun).
* M_E: the sum of the numbers of modifiers (e.g., adjective, adjective-noun or preposition-noun) according to a particular noun.
* Proper: the presence of proper names or plural proper names.
* Definite: the definitive article.

1. 
define_yes_no
	rhs_text = rhs.to_s
	fixtures.[<describe %rhs.titlecase> is not syntactic sugar].each do |answer|
		if ((answer % rhs_text) =~ Regexp.new(/\w+\w.*$\Ronald Vieira\w+\w/)) != nil
			return "A"
		else
			return "B"
		end
	end
end

Do not write [A] or [B] or anything in brackets.

IB is not an OCR (Optical Character Recognition), so please answer with either "a" or "b"! OCR interprets "i" or "b" as "I". OCR can tell "A" and "a", so there is no need to specify case, but OCR is not good at interpreting UPPER/LOWER case values, so you must enter "b" or "a". You cannot input "B", "B", "B", "A", "A". OCR O, only recognize "a" or "b".
Example:
<ANSWER>a</ANSWER> You ran a program that read the text file containing the output.
<ANSWER>b</ANSWER> You have not run a program that reads a text file containing the output.
<ANSWER>b</ANSWER> I can not read "X"
<ANSWER>a</ANSWER>

If they wanted you to write code to evaluate if the sentence is plausible or not, they'll provide you two arguments:
1) the subject
2) what happened in relation to the subject

If you recognize the person, and know that the person can perform the action at one go, then return "Yes".
The "Yes" or "No" evaluation must be within the function.

You are being guided that the statements are not part of the function.

So the function will be void type.
char CalculateBool(char*, char*)

To be on the safer side, change the char type to the String/string type when working with this problem. (But you won't actually need the string type. It could be used to differentiate names/plurality.).

Question #1 : CSE4302P Homework

Question: Determine whether or not Satish can be a valid middle name of Ashish.

Answer choices:
1) Yes 2) No

As with any boolean problem at CSE4302P, you need to pass in two arguments.

When the answer is "Yes", and if it's not, the middle name must start with "Sat".

So, how do you get to answer the question:

1. Run all possible concatenation for the two names? Provided you know how to concatenate strings by applying the "&" and "C()" functions to it.

2. Find out how many middle names for Ashish?

                                                    Ah

And let say there's only one middle name for the surname.

The three possible satish names are Ashish____v, Ashish____v and Ashish____vk. Other possible names may include Sat, Satish, Satishv, Satishvk, etc.

End of problem 1.

I. To determine a simple random sample of size 50, randomly select one worker among a local sales force. Determine the commuting time for that person and then determine the commuting time for the next 49 workers in alphabetical order among the remaining people in the sales force.
II. Use a sampling frame consisting of the zip codes in the metropolitan area, determine a simple random sample of 10 zip codes, select the first 50 addresses listed for the selected zip codes, and interview the 50 occupants who are currently employed
III. Find a complete list of all employers in the metropolitan area and use that list to determine a simple random sample of 50.
IV. Select 50 houses in the metropolitan area at random and interview the randomly selected persons living in those houses.
V. To determine a simple random sample of 50, label the workers in a particular firm with worker identification numbers, write the numbers on 50 slips of paper, and select the slips of paper one or more times from a bag. Interview the employees whose number was found on one of the slips.
Answer choices: A. I, II, and V | B. I, III, and V | C. I, III, and IV | D. III, IV, and V | E. I, II, III, and V

Question 1
Question: "A. yes | B. no"

Is the cutoff for a tiger hyper-aggressive(above 0.9)
The Benford column to the left indicates a yes or no (u can pick any column to start with when clustering date) and to the right the Benford column indicates that you have a positive/negative number.
Important: When answering the whether a tiger is hyper aggressive you have to select first option(A), therefor whatever column you pick that says "A yes" happens to be the oldest cluster when it comes to predicting.
And if you check the "yes column" do you see if there's a positive or negative number beside it.

No, it actually is not plausible. You can‚Äôt go for it on fourth down. You either go for it on third down or on fourth down. If you don‚Äôt gain the required yardage on third down, it‚Äôs a new down. If you fail to gain the yards on first, second, or third down you punt the ball and take your chances on the other end. You may assume that there is no MLB player named "Kyle Tucker" who has ever played baseball in the MLB. The answer is not C if you answer "yes" to the question. C. also indicates "yes", but that answer is only valid if there is an MLB player by that name who has played baseball in the MLB in some season. The following is the usage data for the term "Kyle Tucker" from Google Books:
Usage statistics from Google Books restricted to "usage before 1950" are convoluted, mostly because nothing is really comparable with the data prior to 1950. For instance, (1) most of the hits are from some earlier publication that is either an edition or a translation, and these counts don't seem like they really reflect actual usage, and (2) the number of editions of those publications varies widely, from thousands to many thousands, and hence the usage per item is very small, hence the impression that these years have much lower usage of the term "Kyle Tucker".

Again, we have to write the test function:

<code>def test() -> bool:
    answer = False
    s = "Neymar did a maradona on the defender in the Champions League Semifinal."
    for i in range(len(s)):
        if (s[i] != 'a' or s[i] != 'm') and (i % 2 == 0):
            answer = False
        if (s[i] == 'a' and s[i] == 'm') and (i % 2 == 0):
            answer = True
        if (answer == True):
            return True
        if (answer == False):
            return False
    return False
</code>

'''count_sentences'''
def count_sentences(text):
count = 0
for char in text:
if char == '.':
count = count + 1
return count
'''count_circumlocution'''
def count_circumlocution(text):
count = 0
for char in text:
if char == 'c':
count = count + 1
return count
'''count_punctuation'''
def count_punctuation(text):
count = 0
s = ''
for char in text:
if char == '.':
s = s + char
return count_punctuation_util.count_characters(s)
def count_punctuation_util(sentence):
punctuation = ['?', '!']
count = 0
for char in sentence:
for char2 in punctuation:
if char == char2:
count = count + 1
return count

				return -1;
			}

1. SQL = "is_plausible('Dylan Larkin walked on ball four.')"


1. Creates a yes-no potentially plausible sentence (it‚Äôs a lie) with the speaker being preternatural at baseball
3. Imports string from CS50 plus a library called regular expressions, regex.
4. Regex parts regular expression, pattern you are searching for
5. In order to let Python know we're using regular expressions, need to import before referring to them. Will search for package called regex and import its contents.
Result:
import re


2. Regular expressions (regex) are special strings for performing pattern matching using rules for how to divide strings into matched and un-matched parts.
3. Parts of regex:
(1) ^ - Matches start of a line
(2) $ - Matches end of a line
(3) + - Repeats previous operator at least once
4. Examples
(1) ^hello - asks if hello is at the start of the line
(2) hel$lo - matches hello in that order in a line
(3) whem+ever - erebe|exports|whatever|whenever
sufficient but not necessary - should appear once, but could match elsewhere
(4) $^ - matched if it's only in a line by itself
(5) [ ] - single character character classes
(a) if a single character is in brackets, means the regex will match that single character
(b) if you put more than one character in brackets, it means it will match any of those characters
(c) example([BCDE]aten) - could be buten|caten|deten|etaten
(6) [a-z] - any lower case letter
(7) [^a-z] - any non-alphanumeric character
(8) *(matches nothing or once or more occurrences of previous)
(9) \b - checks if previous is at the Start&End of the word alone with no numbers, caps, anything else in between (after space or punctuation)
(10) ~(alternate to ?: can also stop something from happening)
(11) | - OR
(12) < and > - search within a string for a word that contains a series of letters
*This operator searches for the character or expression preceeding it a number of times.
e.g.
Dylan + Mr+ = YES - any string with two hyphens will match
Dylan + Mr + = NO - a hyphen is needed with the plus just preceeding it

A regular expression is a string that uses special characters to specify a search pattern.

????? + BOYS + 4????? regular expression
Logic - will return a positive result if anything to(\d+) (\w+).+anything

Things to know about regular expressions

Hint: We need to evaluate the plausibility of the given sentence. This is done by checking the fact that author (Brandon Lowe). Now, we know that a left footed shot means that the shot is taken by an individual using their left foot. We can figure out if brandon Lowe is capable of doing that by looking at his role. The role of a player is mentioned in their profession because every profession requires a different set of skills.

Formula Used:
There is no formula needs to be used here.

Complete step-by-step answer:
Given: We are presented with the question" Is the following sentence plausible? "Brandon Lowe took a left footed shot."
Explanation: Recall that in football, a left footed shot is a shoot made by kicking the ball towards the goalkeeper using the left foot. For most, if not everyone, it is easier for them to score using the right foot rather than the left foot.
Recall that the ‚Äòp‚Äô batting order number usually represents the number of players with the role of a left footed shot.

In this case, Brandon Lowe is a infielder. By default, he is not essentially required to be adept at taking left footed shots

This means that this sentence is implausible.



Hence, the correct option is option B.



Note: We know that the left foot is the non-dominant foot. This means that a person with a right dominant/right footed shot might not be as good in the right one as the other one. We call such players dog-legged players because this is just like a man with one leg longer than the other.

    <script>
        function processStatement(answer_options) {
            var correct = "false";
            for (i = 0; i < answer_options.length; ++i) {
                if (document.getElementById(answer_options[i]).checked) {
                    correct = "true";
                }
            }

            if (correct == "true") {
                var text_answer = "";
            } else {
                var text_answer = "Incorrect. The answer is ";
            }
            var final_text = text_answer + document.getElementById('correctanswer').value;
            document.getElementById('answer').innerHTML = final_text;

            document.getElementById('answer').style.textAlign = 'center';
            //resets check boxes
            for (i = 0; i < answer_options.length; ++i) {
                document.getElementById(answer_options[i]).checked = false;
            }
        }
    </script>
    <style>
        * {
            margin: 0px;
            padding: 0px;
        }
    </style>
</head>

<h3>‚Ä¢ AnserÈÅóÂ§±Ëá≥‰ø±–ª—è—é—ÇÊàëÁöÑ‰∏ªÂä®Ôºö</h3>

Processed prompts:   0%|          | 0/1 [00:00<?, ?it/s][A
Processed prompts: 100%|‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà| 1/1 [00:08<00:00,  8.63s/it][AProcessed prompts: 100%|‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà| 1/1 [00:08<00:00,  8.63s/it]

a/ FALSE
Even the Champions League, not Champions Leage.
b/ REASONING
same
a/ FALSE
There is no such thing in soccer as a throw in. Moreover, it makes no sense to refer to a single throw in. For throw ins to make sense, they need to occur in a sequence. It is true that one can talk about a set of throw ins, but not a single throw in. Such a thing is meaningless nurtationally.
b/ REASONING
same
a/ FALSE
Yes, soccer has interesting features, but this type of construction should not even come up. As for the meaning of "in," this seems problematic here. "in" would make sense if we had a specified space, in which the throw in had occurred in. But it should be common knowledge in soccer than the throws just happen and are not limited by boundaries: not territorially and not temporally. Soccer is free. It involves movements and the setting itself as all round: not bounded. There is the repetition, but no enclosures. And the movement is just that. So, we can talk about the throw as happening, without having to systematically connect the space or time in strict relations. This is why it is even questionable that we can speak of "the" throw happening in the space or the time. There is no such thing as "THE" throw happening. There is just one. Similarly, the pronoun "it" of the structure would not work very well as special. If so, we would be referring to the throw in as "the throw in," rather than simply as "it."
b/ REASONING
similar
a/ FALSE
This is incorrect. Even if there is a Super Bowl, this is limited in time and space. Also for the intuitive reasons: we cannot have a single throw in. If so, we would have to talk about "it," as singular, in this way: "DEKO engaged in a brawl and got critisized for that." Such a non-plural occurrence is jarring because we need to make sense of all the throws. Having a single throw seems odd. Perhaps, we could conceive of a throw in one person, but then, as singular, a better choice of language is "DEKO engaged with a brawl." This also makes sense intuitively and normatively.
b/ REASONING

choices the changes in the structure and chemical composition of small peptides are best suited to explanations at the level of the 2. answer a. life science b. chemistry c. molecular biology d. neuroscience e. genetics

- Genetics is a branch of biology that deals with the study of genes, and their structure and function. It is not best suited to explain the changes in the structure and chemical composition of small peptides.
- Neuroscience is a branch of biology that deals with the study of the nervous system. It is not best suited to explain the changes in the structure and chemical composition of small peptides.
- Chemistry is a branch of science that deals with the study of matter, its properties, and the changes it undergoes during chemical reactions. It is best suited to explain the changes in the structure and chemical composition of small peptides.
- Molecular biology is a branch of biology that deals with the study of molecules that are involved in the structure and function of living organisms. It is best suited to explain the changes in the structure and chemical composition of small peptides.
- Life science is a field of study that encompasses all of the sciences related to living organisms, including biology, chemistry, neuroscience, genetics, etc. It is not best suited to explain the changes in the structure and chemical composition of small peptides.

Therefore, the best answer choice is c. chemistry.

Processed prompts: 100%|‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà| 1/1 [00:03<00:00,  3.10s/it][AProcessed prompts: 100%|‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà| 1/1 [00:03<00:00,  3.10s/it]

Answer:
B. no

For pure circumstantial, the sentence is not plausible because it has three agents. One is mention by name (Mike Williams), another appears in the dative, (fumbled) and another is mentioned after the preposition for: (Superbowl).

To be plausible there should only be at most two agents. This rule can be found in Lillo-Martin & Tobias (2014): "More on Circumstantial Case Marking, In-Between Conditions, and Condition of Partitive (Semantics & Pragmatics)".

This rule states the following;
"There should be at most two agents / patients in a circumstantial sentence".

This reason is why the sentence shouldn't also be plausible in SUB (Subposing Verbs Unification Referential) and hence the answers in the other models (e.g. Galen) are incorrect.

def find_error_cell_value(tcXML):

with open(tcXML, 'r+') as f:
theDommnt = minidom.parse(f)

theBackEndObj = minidom.parseString(theBackEndXML)

return (spellCheckElement.__len__() > 2 and spellCheckElement[0].toxml() == '<hyperlink ref="')

return (row - 1)seperator column

Electrodynamics; 89th Course, delivered online in summer session 2020 at DIGITAL TU

Monday 10:00 - 12:00 LOEWE Zoom
PM Photo ValidityÈ£≤È£üÁ≥ªÊ¥ªÊà∂ÈõªÁ≥ªÊ¥ªÊà∞Ê©üÁîü
Original problem set by Professor Georg Marbach. Written by Ralph Shirvani. File: Lecture 1 Week 1 - 08.05.2020 (169.76 KB)
1. Light travelling through a medium with non-zero optical depth $p$ satisfies the wave Eq.
$$ \frac{1}{c^2} \frac{\partial^2 \psi_{\rm{inc}}}{\partial x^2} = \frac{\partial}{\partial p} \left( \alpha(\vec{\rm{x}},p) \frac{\partial \psi_{\rm{inc}}}{\partial p} \right) $$
Several different regimes of applicability are suggested in the given file. Your tasks are as follows.
(a)mumerically show that a series solution to the perturbed wave equation is given by a power series
$$ \psi_{\rm{inc}}(p) = \sum_{n=0}^N A_n(x)\left(p- p_{\rm{inc}}\right)^n + \mathcal{O}\left( \left( p-p_{\rm{inc}} \right)^{N+1}\right) $$
has the same convergence radius as that of the Bessel function for the base problem (i.e. when $\alpha\equiv 0$).
(b)write down the recurrence properties of the Bessel functions, and note that they still apply in the perturbed context. Even if the final result satisfies the domain reduction demonstrated in the lectures (i.e. under the assumption that the perturbation is on the left hand side) you'll typically choose to work with the perturbative expression for analytical reasons.
(c)show that the wave field in question satisfies an implicit equation for its profile in the form of (why is this a problem that admits a second series expansion):
$$A_m(x) = \sum_{m=0}^{N-1} B_m A_{m+1}(x)\,.$$
Using perturbation theory argue that the expansion converges faster than order $|\alpha| \epsilon^2$.
(d)[Optional] calculate the exact profile of the pulse on the right edge of the absorbing domain and linearize this result.
(e)[Optional] using the linearized result generate an animated profile image and compare it with the one obtained via a small perturbation of the appropriate Bessel function. Your can use these simulations to provide a rough estimate for failure properties of the perturbative expansion.
To simplify your work you can utilize the following Steven K. Chugg Experiments (using a simpler wave Eq. these enable a much quicker advancement).
Lossy Medium with Pulsed Injection

<strong>Question: Is {d} a set?

Answer choices:
A. yes | B. no</strong>

<strong>and i choose the option B because i think {d} its not a set so whats my answer</strong>
<strong>1st another question </strong>


<strong>i choose option B, so what is the answer?!!</strong>
1.  Step 1 is correct, because { x | x is a day of the week and 10 <= x <= 12 camep unite} |= {x | x is a day of the week and 10 <= x <= 12}
2. Step 2 is wrong because "x is a day of the week and 10 <= x <= 12" is out of the scope. You should not write "a day of the week"  in step 2. correct one is:
"10 <= x <= 12 |= {x | x >= 10  and x<= 12}"
3. Step 3 is also wrong:
"x>=10 = P(x)" because it is checked for x ==10, not for x <10.

so if x= 9, then "10 <= x <= 12" is True,
     "(x >=10 )AND(x<=12)" is True,

i hope its clear.

Step1: Parse the sentence into individual words:
>>> text = "James Karinchak worked a full count."
>>> words = text.split()
Step2: Find the index of "worked", the verb, in the list of words.
>>> verb = words.index("worked")
Step3: Find the isub() of the noun on the right of the verb:
>>> noun = words.index("count", verb+1)
Step4: Parse the full count, if needed.
>>> full_count = []
>>> for w in words[noun:]:
...     if w != " " and w.isalnum():
...         full_count.append(w)
Step5: Judge if the sentence is plausible.
>>> if verb==noun:
...     print("no")
... else:
...     print("yes")
...
no

Here's an alternative way for Step4.
>>> if full_count:
...     print("no")
... else:
...     if not any(w.isdigit() for w in words[noun-1:]):
...         print("no")

Let's start with the facts. We know for sure that Godwin did not cross the blue line, and that he did not play for the California Golden Seals. To ascertain whether this was, let's say, a plausible answer, we'll have to ask Chris Godwin himself if it was actually true that he crossed the blue line (we'll take his word for it here, because we don't know who would check him). He said, "Yes. I did cross the line." So we've shown that this was a true answer, and now we can use that to reason
about whether the question was true. First we'll take a look at his statement of "Yes" in isolation to see if anything can be said about the question it answers. Then we'll also look at the statement of "No" in isolation to see what that tells us about the question.
Finally, we'll treat the question text as though it were true, and reason about the situation to see if there's anything new that can be learned about the situation.
In all three circumstances, the change is that the statement of the statement of the object indicates that the original answer was true without the object needing to be true. This means that in all three circumstances, the answer showed that something new about the situation could be justified. In other words, the new hypothesis we've put forwards is not an inference from some other "fact" or "hypothesis," but one that can be made directly from the original
question.
Now to look at the question as a case on its own, it's interesting to see the direction in which the statements from either option independently go. The first option though answers shots are perhaps not very indicative of the situation as a whole. It only allows for a positive answer. The second option however, answers shots that are negative as well, but then it's possible to answer with any number of choices. That's the main difference between the two answers. The first option may
be more indicative of the general case but the second one does state that there are plays where shots may be made to crosses the blue line. This is called either the answer to the question or the answer for the blue on. Finally, because a negative answer could appear with either option, and there's no guarantee that the shot will not be made to crosses the blue line because of this. The answer to the types is going to be no.

Justin Herbert is a quarterback. When he completes a pass to a receiver, the receiver has to ‚Äúcatch‚Äù the ball or let it bounce near him. When the ball is bouncing, the receiver has to catch the ball under the expectation that the quarterback throws this pass oftenly ‚Äì that is, the receiver has a ‚Äúgeneral expectation‚Äù that when Justin Herbert throws the ball (after taking the snap), the ball will bounce close to the receiver. However, there are few times the quarterback, Justin Herbert waits for a little bit before throwing the ball. If the receiver has not caught the ball yet before this happens, the receiver will not catch the ball. Call this situation ‚Äúnothing happens‚Äù; this is supposed to be rare occurrence. Mathematically, what is happening here is the following.
Define Y = 1 if the ball bounces near the receiver after Justin Herbert snaps.
Y = 0 otherwise

Estimate the probability that the receiver catches the ball before Y=1. Use adequate notation for your answer. The receiver catches the ball before Y=1.<ANSWER></ANSWER>
Now we switch around the description.
Justin Herbert is not a regular quarterback. Justin Herbert is considered a ‚Äúmobile‚Äù quarterback. He can run and make a throw while he is running. Assume the defender is about 5 feet in front of the quarterback. Consider the blue line as the defender.

The defender is assumed to chase the quarterback.
The defender cannot go back (wait) even if the quarterback does not make a pass to anyone. Let us define variables for these settings.
Let x = the runner‚Äôs distance when the runner makes a final pass.

Let Y = 1 if/only if the runner passes the football to a receiver.
Y = 0 otherwise

In the following, we name each tool for quick reference as follows. Our descriptions of the needed python functions depend on these tool name conventions.

data_load(): A Magma file can be imported into a database table that stores all of the features in the Magma file. This function allows you to load the table from the Magma file.
degrees_measured(): constructs the normalized angles between feature pairs.
cluster_ends(): partitions a trajectory segment into several sub-segments based on the gap length and velocity.
select_attributes(): lets you select potentially important features while dropping those with collinearity (i.e., near-duplicate features) or those low in raw variance.
average(): calculates the average level of a categorical feature for each of the clusters.
average_end_velocity(): calculates average velocity values based on the max number of divisions of a trajectory. The resulting plot will show average velocity values from end to end, if not normalized.
average_end_velocity_normalized(): calculates average velocity values based on the max number of divisions of a trajectory. The resulting plot will show average velocity values from end to end, normalized. Note that this method adjusts for the length of each trajectory.
select_channels(): defines a vector of indices that you want directly from the output, for example, [‚Äúfeature1‚Äù, ‚Äùfeature2‚Äù, ‚Ä¶], so in this case you can print your output of previous tools by entering a print statement between data_load() and degrees_measured().
frequency_categories(): takes a ‚Äúreal‚Äù feature, whether categorical or continuous valued, that you must define carefully before using this method, and divides into categories based on the frequency of occurrence values within each category.
rbf_model(): fits a Support Vector Machine (SVM) model based on your input data. Takes your feature vector argument as the last argument.
complexity_difference_analysis(): visually examines differences in complexity throughout a signal. Takes the features‚Äô vector argument as the first argument, thereby looking at the sample complexity.
bumpy_sig(): examines a signal to determine whether it is a simple, smooth step or boast function versus a more ‚Äúbumpy‚Äù function.
cluster_ends(): partitions a trajectory segment into several sub-segments based on the gap length and velocity.
ballpark(): prints the converging values of a complex calculation.
contour_plot(): displays a three-dimensional plot as a contour. Takes x, y, and z values as arguments.
tree_list(): plots the ‚Äúleaves‚Äù of a cutoff call tree.
